{"title_page": "The Mutations", "text_new": "{{missing information|the film's production, and theatrical/VHS releases|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Mutations(The Freakmaker)\n| image          = \"The_Mutations\".jpeg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = British theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jack Cardiff]]\n| producer       = Robert D. Weinbach\n| writer         = Edward Mann<br>Robert D. Weinbach\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Donald Pleasence]]<br>[[Tom Baker (English actor)|Tom Baker]]<br> [[Brad Harris]]<br>[[Julie Ege]]\n| music          = [[Basil Kirchin]]<br>Jack Nathan (uncredited)\n| cinematography = [[Paul Beeson]]\n| editing        = John Trumper\n| studio         = Cyclone<br>Getty Pictures Corp.\n| distributor    = Columbia-Warner (UK)<br>[[Columbia Pictures]] (US)\n| released       = October 1974 (UK)<br>25 September 1974 (US)\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom<br>United States<ref>{{cite web|title=The Mutations|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55581|website=American Film Institute|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n'''''The Mutations''''' is a low-budget 1974 British-American [[science fiction]]/[[horror film]] directed by [[Jack Cardiff]]. The film was also released under the title '''''The Freakmaker'''''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6beb2394 |title=The Mutations (1973) &#124; BFI |publisher=Explore.bfi.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{more plot|date=July 2018}}\nThis movie directed by Academy Award-winning cinematographer/director Jack Cardiff in the 1970's depicts A deranged genetic scientist, Professor Nolter(Donald Pleasence), a man with self proclaimed noble to break through to the next stage in human evolution, through the crossbreeding cannibalistic Venus flytraps with abducted college students [[guinea pig]]s from his own class. \"I'll create a race of plants that can walk, and men that can take root,\" <ref>Bob, Joe. \"Joe Bob's Mail Bag.\" The San Francisco Examiner 22 March. 1992: 229. Print.</ref>through an exploitation of certain nucleic acids <ref>Weiler A.H. \"'The Mutations,' British Sci-Fi, Arrives.\" The New York Times 26 Sept. 1974: 26. Print.</ref>. The failed experimental mutants are then given to a cruel circus freakshow owner, Mr. Lynch(Tom Baker known for Dr. Who) who exploits them to the fullest. However, the mutants and the circus freaks will not be denied justice. Inspired by Tod Browning's film Freaks with a science fiction twist, this film is full of pseudo scientific jargon, stop motion visuals, makeup effects, references to psychedelics, comical gore, nudity, and by the standards of modern viewers a distasteful exploitation of actors with actual genetic disabilities as well as some made up disabilities including a man with rubber-bones known as the Human Pretzel, a lady with reptilian skin(Alligator Lady), the Monkey Woman, the Human Pincusion and Popeye.<ref>Price, Michael, \"The Freakmaker.\" Fortworth Star-Telegram 6 April 1985: 6. Print.</ref><ref>Lucas, Tim. Video Watchdog magazine Oct. 2005</ref>. Nonetheless it grabs attention among the other scenes of \"freaks\" it depicts a reversed stop motion capture of the professor reviving a moldy orange, and the professor feeding a bunny rabbit to a Venus flytrap. A dissonant and jumbled orchestral score composed by Basil Kirchen provides a perfect backdrop to the overacting and dramatics of the actors in this intriguing 1970's horror film which has been restored on DVD after decades of floating in obscurity. <ref>Price, Michael, \"'The Freakmaker' now on video.\" Fortworth Star-Telegram 5 Oct. 1984: 3. Print.</ref>\n==Cast==\n* [[Donald Pleasence]] as Professor Nolter \n* [[Tom Baker (English actor)|Tom Baker]] as Lynch \n* [[Brad Harris]] as Brian Redford \n* [[Julie Ege]] as Hedi \n* [[Michael Dunn (actor)|Michael Dunn]] as Burns \n* [[Scott Antony]] as Tony \n* [[Jill Haworth]] as Lauren \n* [[Olga Anthony]] as Bridget \n* [[Lisa Collings]] as Prostitute\n* [[Joan Scott (actress)|Joan Scott]] as Landlady \n* [[Toby Lennon]] as Tramp \n* [[John Wreford]] as Policeman\n* [[Eithne Dunne]] as Nurse\n* [[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]] as Doctor\n\n==Release==\n{{expand section|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] by Subversive Cinema on September 27, 2005. Subversive Cinema later re-released the film on January 29, 2008 including with it commentary tracks with Jack Cardiff, Robert Weinbach, and Brad Harris as a part of its 2-Disk ''Greenhouse Gore'' movie pack. It was last released by Desert Island Films on February 18, 2012.<ref name=\"allmovierelease\">{{cite web |title=The Mutations (1974) - Jack Cardiff |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-mutations-v103272/releases |website=Allmovie.com |publisher=AllMovie |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=August 2014}}\nAuthor and film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] awarded the film  2 out of 4 stars, criticizing the film's predictable story and what he called \"grotesque elements and characters\".<ref name=\"Maltin2013\">{{cite book|author=Leonard Maltin|title=Leonard Maltin's Movie Guide: 2014 Edition : the Modern Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9CmmmwEACAAJ|year=2013|publisher=Plume Books|isbn=978-0-14-218055-6|page=964}}</ref> [[TV Guide]] awarded the film 1/5 stars, writing, \"Though at times the film is so bad it's unintentionally funny, it has a certain cruelty to it.\"<ref name=\"tvguiderev\">{{cite web |title=The Mutations - Movie Reviews and Movie Ratings |url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/the-mutations/review/126841/ |website=TV Guide.com |publisher=TV Guide |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> \nMichael H. Price of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, gave the movie 3 stars and praised the movie comparing it to Tod Browning's Freaks, and calling the effects \"at once shocking and fascinating\" and praising its \"dissonant orchestral score\" which he claims \"adds mightily to the mood of unease and gathering madness.\"<ref>Price, Michael, \"'The Freakmaker' now on video.\" Fortworth Star-Telegram 5 Oct. 1984: 3. Print.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Allmovie|103272|The Mutations}}\n* {{IMDb title|0070423|The Mutations}}\n* {{Rotten tomatoes|the_mutations|The Mutations}}\n*{{tcmdb title|84255|The Mutations}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Speculative fiction/Horror|Science fiction}}\n{{Jack Cardiff}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mutations, The}}\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:1970s monster movies]]\n[[Category:British monster movies]]\n[[Category:1974 horror films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jack Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Basil Kirchin]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:1970s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction horror films]]\n", "text_old": "{{missing information|the film's production, and theatrical/VHS releases|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Mutations(The Freakmaker)\n| image          = \"The_Mutations\".jpeg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = British theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jack Cardiff]]\n| producer       = Robert D. Weinbach\n| writer         = Edward Mann<br>Robert D. Weinbach\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Donald Pleasence]]<br>[[Tom Baker (English actor)|Tom Baker]]<br> [[Brad Harris]]<br>[[Julie Ege]]\n| music          = [[Basil Kirchin]]<br>Jack Nathan (uncredited)\n| cinematography = [[Paul Beeson]]\n| editing        = John Trumper\n| studio         = Cyclone<br>Getty Pictures Corp.\n| distributor    = Columbia-Warner (UK)<br>[[Columbia Pictures]] (US)\n| released       = October 1974 (UK)<br>25 September 1974 (US)\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom<br>United States<ref>{{cite web|title=The Mutations|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55581|website=American Film Institute|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n'''''The Mutations''''' is a low-budget 1974 British-American [[science fiction]]/[[horror film]] directed by [[Jack Cardiff]]. The film was also released under the title '''''The Freakmaker'''''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b6beb2394 |title=The Mutations (1973) &#124; BFI |publisher=Explore.bfi.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{more plot|date=July 2018}}\nA deranged genetic scientist with self proclaimed noble intentions professor attempts to break through to the next stage in human evolution, through crossbreeding cannibalistic Venus flytraps with abducted college students [[guinea pig]]s from his own class which he is the professor of. \"I'll create a race of plants that can walk, and men that can take root,\" <ref>Bob, Joe. \"Joe Bob's Mail Bag.\" The San Francisco Examiner 22 March. 1992: 229. Print.</ref>through an exploitation of certain nucleic acids <ref>Weiler A.H. \"'The Mutations,' British Sci-Fi, Arrives.\" The New York Times 26 Sept. 1974: 26. Print.</ref>. The failed experimental mutants are then given to a cruel circus freakshow owner who exploits them to the fullest. However, the mutants and the circus freaks will not be denied justice. Inspired by Tod Browning's film Freaks with a science fiction twist, this film is full of pseudo scientific jargon, stop motion visuals, references to psychedelics, comical gore, nudity, and by the standards of modern viewers a distasteful exploitation of actors with actual genetic disabilities as well as some made up disabilities including a man with rubber-bones and a lady with reptilian skin<ref>Price, Michael, \"The Freakmaker.\" Fortworth Star-Telegram 6 April 1985: 6. Print.</ref>. Nonetheless it grabs attention among the other scenes of \"freaks\" it depicts the professor reviving a moldy orange, and feeding a bunny rabbit to a Venus flytrap. A dissonant and jumbled orchestral score by Basil Kirchen provides a perfect backdrop to the overacting and dramatics of the actors in this intriguing 1970's horror film which has been restored on DVD after decades of floating in obscurity. <ref>Price, Michael, \"'The Freakmaker' now on video.\" Fortworth Star-Telegram 5 Oct. 1984: 3. Print.</ref>\n==Cast==\n* [[Donald Pleasence]] as Professor Nolter \n* [[Tom Baker (English actor)|Tom Baker]] as Lynch \n* [[Brad Harris]] as Brian Redford \n* [[Julie Ege]] as Hedi \n* [[Michael Dunn (actor)|Michael Dunn]] as Burns \n* [[Scott Antony]] as Tony \n* [[Jill Haworth]] as Lauren \n* [[Olga Anthony]] as Bridget \n* [[Lisa Collings]] as Prostitute\n* [[Joan Scott (actress)|Joan Scott]] as Landlady \n* [[Toby Lennon]] as Tramp \n* [[John Wreford]] as Policeman\n* [[Eithne Dunne]] as Nurse\n* [[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]] as Doctor\n\n==Release==\n{{expand section|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] by Subversive Cinema on September 27, 2005. Subversive Cinema later re-released the film on January 29, 2008 as a part of its 2-Disk ''Greenhouse Gore'' movie pack. It was last released by Desert Island Films on February 18, 2012.<ref name=\"allmovierelease\">{{cite web |title=The Mutations (1974) - Jack Cardiff |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-mutations-v103272/releases |website=Allmovie.com |publisher=AllMovie |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=August 2014}}\nAuthor and film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] awarded the film  2 out of 4 stars, criticizing the film's predictable story and what he called \"grotesque elements and characters\".<ref name=\"Maltin2013\">{{cite book|author=Leonard Maltin|title=Leonard Maltin's Movie Guide: 2014 Edition : the Modern Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9CmmmwEACAAJ|year=2013|publisher=Plume Books|isbn=978-0-14-218055-6|page=964}}</ref> [[TV Guide]] awarded the film 1/5 stars, writing, \"Though at times the film is so bad it's unintentionally funny, it has a certain cruelty to it.\"<ref name=\"tvguiderev\">{{cite web |title=The Mutations - Movie Reviews and Movie Ratings |url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/the-mutations/review/126841/ |website=TV Guide.com |publisher=TV Guide |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> \nMichael H. Price of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, gave the movie 3 stars and praised the movie comparing it to Tod Browning's Freaks, and calling the effects \"at once shocking and fascinating\" and praising its \"dissonant orchestral score\" which he claims \"adds mightily to the mood of unease and gathering madness.\"<ref>Price, Michael, \"'The Freakmaker' now on video.\" Fortworth Star-Telegram 5 Oct. 1984: 3. Print.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Allmovie|103272|The Mutations}}\n* {{IMDb title|0070423|The Mutations}}\n* {{Rotten tomatoes|the_mutations|The Mutations}}\n*{{tcmdb title|84255|The Mutations}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Speculative fiction/Horror|Science fiction}}\n{{Jack Cardiff}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mutations, The}}\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:1970s monster movies]]\n[[Category:British monster movies]]\n[[Category:1974 horror films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jack Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Basil Kirchin]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:1970s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction horror films]]\n", "name_user": "NCBURDICK", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added more plot from a writer Tim Lucas who was quoted on amazon and on the back of the DVD copy I own", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mutations"