elilla]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Canary Islands]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Spain|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Spain}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n** {{cite web |url=https://www.rtve.es/noticias/20200227/mapa-del-coronavirus-espana-24-casos-siete-comunidades-autonomas/2004681.shtml |title=El mapa del coronavirus en Espa\u00f1a |trans-title=The map of coronavirus in Spain |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[RTVE]] |language=Spanish}}\n** {{cite web |url=https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020/03/30/actualidad/1585589827_546714.html |title=Casos confirmados de coronavirus en Espa\u00f1a y en el mundo |trans-title=Confirmed cases of coronavirus in Spain and in the world |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=Spanish}}\n** {{cite web |url=https://covid19.isciii.es/ |title=Situaci\u00f3n de COVID-19 en Espa\u00f1a |trans-title=Situation of COVID-19 in Spain |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Carlos III Health Institute|ISCIII]] |language=Spanish}}\n* Government-issued information:\n** {{cite web |url=https://www.mscbs.gob.es/en/profesionales/saludPublica/ccayes/alertasActual/nCov-China/home.htm |title=Enfermedad por nuevo coronavirus, COVID-19 |trans-title=New coronavirus disease, COVID-19 |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (Spain)|Ministry of Health]] |language=Spanish}}\n\n{{COVID-19|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Spain]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Spain]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Spain]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Spain|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Spain|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Spain|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "24.233.121.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Spain"}
{"title_page": "University of Dayton School of Law", "text_new": "{{Infobox law school\n | name           = University of Dayton School of Law\n | image          = \n | established    = 1922\n | type           = Private\n | head           = Andrew L. Strauss\n | city           = [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]]\n | state          = [[Ohio]]\n | country        = [[United States]]\n | students       = 300\n | homepage       = [http://law.udayton.edu/ Dayton Law home]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Dayton School of Law (UDSL)''' is a private law school located in [[Dayton, Ohio]]. It is affiliated with the [[University of Dayton]], which is a [[Catholic]] university of the [[Society of Mary (Marianists)|Society of Mary]]. The school is accredited by the [[American Bar Association]] and is a member of the [[Association of American Law Schools]].<ref>http://www.aals.org/about_memberschools.php</ref><ref>http://www.americanbar.org/groups/legal_education/resources/aba_approved_law_schools/by_year_approved.html</ref>\n\nThe school's Class of 2018 is made up of students from across the country, with 51% coming from places other than [[Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/law/about/class_profile.php|title=Class Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe School of Law was first established as the University of Dayton College of Law in 1922 under the guidance of Dean John C. Shea, the former first assistant director of law for [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/about/about-us/history.php|title=History of the University of Dayton School of Law|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref> The college\u2019s first class included two women and one African American. Economic issues during the Great Depression led the law school to close its doors in 1935.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe law school reopened in September 1974 under its current name.<ref name=\":0\" /> In July 1997, the school's current location, Joseph E. Keller Hall, was opened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/library/zimmerman_library_history.php|title=History of the Zimmerman Law Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\n=== Two-year J.D. Program ===\nThe school offers its students the option of pursuing a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] at an accelerated pace. Students may earn a law degree in two years by beginning in May and going to school full-time including summer terms.<ref>http://www.udayton.edu/law/academics/jd_program/two_year_option.php</ref>\n\n=== Online Hybrid Juris Doctor (JD) Program ===\nThrough a hybrid J.D. program called Law@Dayton, students will be able to take most of their classes online, coming to campus for only a week each semester.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.law.com/2018/06/11/ahead-of-the-curve-here-come-the-hybrids/|title=Ahead of the Curve: Here Come the Hybrids {{!}} Law.com|work=Law.com|access-date=2018-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://onlinelaw.udayton.edu/online-jd|title=The Online Hybrid Juris Doctor Program {{!}} Law@Dayton|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref> The program received approval from the [[American Bar Association]] and started in 2019.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Program In Law And Technology (PILT) ===\nIn 1989, the law school created the Program in Law and Technology (PILT), one of the first programs of its kind in the country. PILT offers courses in patent law, copyright and trademark law, business dimensions of intellectual property law, cyberspace law, entertainment law and the impact of technology on the practice of law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/academics/pilt/index.php|title=Program In Law and Technology|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref> Collaborations with [[Emerson Electric|Emerson]] and [[LexisNexis]] provide hands-on experience in areas of data security and privacy, product liability, regulation and developing new legal products and services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/news/articles/2017/07/udsl_technology_law_school_initiative_emerson_lexisnexis.php|title=The Future Of Lawyering|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Human Rights Collaborative ===\nThrough a partnership with the [[University of Dayton|University of Dayton's]] Human Rights Center, law school students and faculty can work to protect the rights of vulnerable citizens across the world. The collaborative features a course on human rights and joint-research projects between the law school and the center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/academics/udsl_hrc_collaborative/index.php|title=The Dayton Law-Human Rights Center Collaborative|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Concentrations ===\nThe law school offers students the ability to take concentrations in six different areas: Business Law & Compliance, Civil Advocacy & Dispute Resolution, Criminal Law, Human & Civil Rights Law, Law & Technology and Personal & Family Law. The concentrations allow students to develop their skills and knowledge in those specific areas in an effort to give them better training in the field they plan to enter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/law/registrar/concentrations.php|title=Concentrations with Certification|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*Hon. Frank Caruso '82 - 8th Judicial District, Niagara County, Supreme Court Justice<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycourts.gov/COURTS/8jd/Niagara/index.shtml|title=8th Judicial District|last=|first=|date=|website=nycourts.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Hon. Beth Ann Buchanan '97 - U.S. Bankruptcy Judge, Southern District of Ohio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsb.uscourts.gov/judge-buchanan-biography|title=Judge Buchanan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=ohsb.uscourts.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Michael B. Coleman]] '80 - First African-American Mayor of [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/michael_b_coleman.html|title=The Arena: Michael B. Coleman Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=politico.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Hon. Mary Donovan '77 - Ohio 2nd District Court of Appeals Judge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcohio.org/SecondDistrictAppeals/judges.cfm|title=Ohio Second District Court of Appeals|last=|first=|date=|website=mcohio.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Hon. Frank Geraci '77 - Chief U.S. District Judge- Western District of New York<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nywd.uscourts.gov/hon-frank-p-geraci|title=Hon. Frank P. Geraci Jr.|last=|first=|date=|website=nywd.uscourts.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Martin Hamlette '02 - Executive Director, National Medical Association<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmanet.org/page/Executive_Director/Martin-Hamlette-JD-MHA.htm|title=Martin Hamlette JD, MHA|last=|first=|date=|website=nmanet.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[David Joyce (politician)|David P. Joyce]] '82 - [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]], Ohio 14th Congressional District\n*[[Elizabeth A. McClanahan|Hon. Elizabeth A. McClanahan]] '84 - [[Supreme Court of Virginia|Virginia Supreme Court]] Justice\n*[[Jeff Rezabek]] '97 - former [[Montgomery County, Ohio|Montgomery County]] Juvenile Court Judge; Served in [[Ohio House of Representatives]], 43rd District\n*Timothy Young '92 - Ohio Public Defender<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://opd.ohio.gov/About-Us/About-the-Office|title=About the Office|last=|first=|date=|website=opd.ohio.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Douglas J. Swearingen, Jr., '12 - [[Ohio House of Representatives]], 89th District<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews-messenger.com/story/news/2019/08/01/douglas-swearingen-sworn-representative-89th-ohio-house-district/1886760001/|title=Swearingen sworn in as representative to 89th House District|website=The News-Messenger|language=en|access-date=2019-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Notable attendees==\n* John Meehan, the antagonist of the true-crime [[Dirty John|podcast]] and eponymous TV series ''[[Dirty John (TV series)|Dirty John]]''\n\n==Post-Graduation Employment==\n\nAccording to Dayton Law's official 2019 ABA-required disclosures, 76% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, bar passage-required or J.D. preferred employment ten months after graduation, excluding solo-practitioners.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/law/_resources/documents/career_services/employment_stats/aba_employment_summary_for_2016_grads.pdf|title=Employment Summary for 2018 Graduates|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Ohio]] was the primary employment destination for 2018 Dayton Law graduates, with 59% of employed 2018 graduates working in the state.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Costs==\n\nTuition at Dayton Law for traditional first-year students is $35,003 for the 2019-2020 academic year.<ref name=\"Tuition\" /> Books and supplies are estimated at $1,500.<ref name=\"Tuition\" /> Living and personal expenses are estimated at $16,000.<ref name=\"Tuition\" /> The total cost of attendance at Dayton Law for the 2018-2019 academic year is $52,921.<ref name=\"Tuition\">{{cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/admissions/costs.php|title=Tuition and Living Expenses|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Dayton|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' estimated the average indebtedness of 2016 Dayton Law graduates at $108,724.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/grad-debt-rankings/|title=Which Law School Graduates have the most debt?|last=|first=|date=|work=U.S. News & World Report|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://law.udayton.edu/ University of Dayton School of Law]\n\n{{University of Dayton}}\n{{Law Schools of the Midwest}}\n\n{{coord|39|44|26.16|N|84|10|47.28|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dayton Law, University of}}\n[[Category:Catholic law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Ohio]]\n[[Category:University of Dayton|Law]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1922]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law school\n | name           = University of Dayton School of Law\n | image          = \n | established    = 1922\n | type           = Private\n | head           = Andrew L. Strauss\n | city           = [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]]\n | state          = [[Ohio]]\n | country        = [[United States]]\n | students       = 300\n | homepage       = [http://law.udayton.edu/ Dayton Law home]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Dayton School of Law (UDSL)''' is a private law school located in [[Dayton, Ohio]]. It is affiliated with the [[University of Dayton]], which is a [[Catholic]] university of the [[Society of Mary (Marianists)|Society of Mary]]. The school is accredited by the [[American Bar Association]] and is a member of the [[Association of American Law Schools]].<ref>http://www.aals.org/about_memberschools.php</ref><ref>http://www.americanbar.org/groups/legal_education/resources/aba_approved_law_schools/by_year_approved.html</ref>\n\nThe school's Class of 2018 is made up of students from across the country, with 51% coming from places other than [[Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/law/about/class_profile.php|title=Class Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe School of Law was first established as the University of Dayton College of Law in 1922 under the guidance of Dean John C. Shea, the former first assistant director of law for [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/about/about-us/history.php|title=History of the University of Dayton School of Law|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref> The college\u2019s first class included two women and one African American. Economic issues during the Great Depression led the law school to close its doors in 1935.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe law school reopened in September 1974 under its current name.<ref name=\":0\" /> In July 1997, the school's current location, Joseph E. Keller Hall, was opened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/library/zimmerman_library_history.php|title=History of the Zimmerman Law Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\n=== Two-year J.D. Program ===\nThe school offers its students the option of pursuing a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] at an accelerated pace. Students may earn a law degree in two years by beginning in May and going to school full-time including summer terms.<ref>http://www.udayton.edu/law/academics/jd_program/two_year_option.php</ref>\n\n=== Online Hybrid Juris Doctor (JD) Program ===\nThrough a hybrid J.D. program called Law@Dayton, students will be able to take most of their classes online, coming to campus for only a week each semester.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.law.com/2018/06/11/ahead-of-the-curve-here-come-the-hybrids/|title=Ahead of the Curve: Here Come the Hybrids {{!}} Law.com|work=Law.com|access-date=2018-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://onlinelaw.udayton.edu/online-jd|title=The Online Hybrid Juris Doctor Program {{!}} Law@Dayton|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref> The program received approval from the [[American Bar Association]] and started in 2019.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Program In Law And Technology (PILT) ===\nIn 1989, the law school created the Program in Law and Technology (PILT), one of the first programs of its kind in the country. PILT offers courses in patent law, copyright and trademark law, business dimensions of intellectual property law, cyberspace law, entertainment law and the impact of technology on the practice of law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/academics/pilt/index.php|title=Program In Law and Technology|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref> Collaborations with [[Emerson Electric|Emerson]] and [[LexisNexis]] provide hands-on experience in areas of data security and privacy, product liability, regulation and developing new legal products and services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/news/articles/2017/07/udsl_technology_law_school_initiative_emerson_lexisnexis.php|title=The Future Of Lawyering|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Human Rights Collaborative ===\nThrough a partnership with the [[University of Dayton|University of Dayton's]] Human Rights Center, law school students and faculty can work to protect the rights of vulnerable citizens across the world. The collaborative features a course on human rights and joint-research projects between the law school and the center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/academics/udsl_hrc_collaborative/index.php|title=The Dayton Law-Human Rights Center Collaborative|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Concentrations ===\nThe law school offers students the ability to take concentrations in six different areas: Business Law & Compliance, Civil Advocacy & Dispute Resolution, Criminal Law, Human & Civil Rights Law, Law & Technology and Personal & Family Law. The concentrations allow students to develop their skills and knowledge in those specific areas in an effort to give them better training in the field they plan to enter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/law/registrar/concentrations.php|title=Concentrations with Certification|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*Hon. Frank Caruso '82 - 8th Judicial District, Niagara County, Supreme Court Justice<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycourts.gov/COURTS/8jd/Niagara/index.shtml|title=8th Judicial District|last=|first=|date=|website=nycourts.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Hon. Beth Ann Buchanan '97 - U.S. Bankruptcy Judge, Southern District of Ohio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsb.uscourts.gov/judge-buchanan-biography|title=Judge Buchanan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=ohsb.uscourts.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Michael B. Coleman]] '80 - First African-American Mayor of [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/michael_b_coleman.html|title=The Arena: Michael B. Coleman Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=politico.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Hon. Mary Donovan '77 - Ohio 2nd District Court of Appeals Judge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcohio.org/SecondDistrictAppeals/judges.cfm|title=Ohio Second District Court of Appeals|last=|first=|date=|website=mcohio.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Hon. Frank Geraci '77 - Chief U.S. District Judge- Western District of New York<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nywd.uscourts.gov/hon-frank-p-geraci|title=Hon. Frank P. Geraci Jr.|last=|first=|date=|website=nywd.uscourts.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Martin Hamlette '02 - Executive Director, National Medical Association<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmanet.org/page/Executive_Director/Martin-Hamlette-JD-MHA.htm|title=Martin Hamlette JD, MHA|last=|first=|date=|website=nmanet.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[David Joyce (politician)|David P. Joyce]] '82 - [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]], Ohio 14th Congressional District\n*[[Elizabeth A. McClanahan|Hon. Elizabeth A. McClanahan]] '84 - [[Supreme Court of Virginia|Virginia Supreme Court]] Justice\n*[[Jeff Rezabek]] '97 - former [[Montgomery County, Ohio|Montgomery County]] Juvenile Court Judge; Served in [[Ohio House of Representatives]], 43rd District\n*Timothy Young '92 - Ohio Public Defender<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://opd.ohio.gov/About-Us/About-the-Office|title=About the Office|last=|first=|date=|website=opd.ohio.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n*Douglas J. Swearingen, Jr., '12 - [[Ohio House of Representatives]], 89th District<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews-messenger.com/story/news/2019/08/01/douglas-swearingen-sworn-representative-89th-ohio-house-district/1886760001/|title=Swearingen sworn in as representative to 89th House District|website=The News-Messenger|language=en|access-date=2019-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Notable attendees==\n* John Meehan, the antagonist of the true-crime [[Dirty John|podcast]] and eponymous TV series ''[[Dirty John (TV series)|Dirty John]]''\n\n==Post-Graduation Employment==\n\nAccording to Dayton Law's official 2019 ABA-required disclosures, 76% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, bar passage-required or J.D. preferred employment ten months after graduation, excluding solo-practitioners.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.udayton.edu/law/_resources/documents/career_services/employment_stats/aba_employment_summary_for_2016_grads.pdf|title=Employment Summary for 2018 Graduates|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Ohio]] was the primary employment destination for 2018 Dayton Law graduates, with 59% of employed 2018 graduates working in the state.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Costs==\n\nTuition at Dayton Law for traditional first-year students is $35,003 for the 2019-2020 academic year.<ref name=\"Tuition\" /> Books and supplies are estimated at $1,500.<ref name=\"Tuition\" /> Living and personal expenses are estimated at $16,000.<ref name=\"Tuition\" /> The total cost of attendance at Dayton Law for the 2018-2019 academic year is $52,921.<ref name=\"Tuition\">{{cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/law/admissions/costs.php|title=Tuition and Living Expenses|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Dayton|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' estimated the average indebtedness of 2016 Dayton Law graduates at $108,724.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/grad-debt-rankings/|title=Which Law School Graduates have the most debt?|last=|first=|date=|work=U.S. News & World Report|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://law.udayton.edu/ University of Dayton School of Law]\n\n{{University of Dayton}}\n{{Law Schools of the Midwest}}\n\n{{coord|39|44|26.16|N|84|10|47.28|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dayton Law, University of}}\n[[Category:Catholic law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Ohio]]\n[[Category:University of Dayton|Law]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1922]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Dayton_School_of_Law"}
{"title_page": "2013 StuSells Toronto Tankard", "text_new": "{{infobox curling\n| Name = 2013 StuSells Toronto Tankard\n| Logo = \n| Size = \n| Host city = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| Arena = [[High Park Club]]\n| Dates = October 11\u201314\n| Men's winner = {{flagicon|ON}} '''Glenn Howard'''\n| Curling club = [[Penetang Curling Club|Penetang CC]], [[Penetanguishene]]\n| Skip = [[Glenn Howard]]\n| Third = [[Wayne Middaugh]]\n| Second = [[Brent Laing]]\n| Lead = [[Craig Savill]]\n| Finalist = {{flagicon|MB}} [[Mike McEwen (curler)|Mike McEwen]]\n| Women's winner = {{flagicon|ON}} '''Allison Flaxey'''\n| Curling club2 = \n| Skip2 = [[Allison Flaxey]]\n| Third2 = [[Katie Pringle]]\n| Second2 = [[Lynn Kreviazuk]]\n| Lead2 = [[Morgan Court]]\n| Finalist2 = {{flagicon|NS}} [[Mary-Anne Arsenault]]\n}}\nThe '''2013 [[StuSells Toronto Tankard]]''' was held from October 11 to 14 at the [[High Park Club]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. The men's event was held as part of the [[2013\u201314 World Curling Tour]], while the women's event was held only as part of the 2013\u201314 Ontario Curling Tour. The men's event was held in a triple-knockout format, while the women's event was held in a round robin format. The purse for the men's event was [[Canadian dollar|CAD]]$45,000, of which the winner, [[Glenn Howard]], received CAD$15,000, while the purse for the women's event was CAD$15,000, of which the winner, [[Allison Flaxey]], received CAD$5,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcurl.com/events.php?task=Event&eventid=3053&view=Contact|title=2013 StuSells Toronto Tankard \u2013 Men's event \u2013 Event/Contact information|publisher=[[World Curling Tour]]|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcurl.com/events.php?task=Event&eventid=3054&view=Contact|title=2013 StuSells Toronto Tankard \u2013 Women's event \u2013 Event/Contact information|publisher=[[World Curling Tour]]|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> In the men's final, Howard defeated [[Mike McEwen (curler)|Mike McEwen]] with a score of 6\u20133, while in the women's final, Flaxey defeated [[Mary-Anne Arsenault]] with a score of 6\u20132.\n\n==Men==\n\n===Teams===\nThe teams are listed as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcurl.com/events.php?task=Event&eventid=3053&view=Teams|title=2013 StuSells Toronto Tankard \u2013 Men's event \u2013 Teams|publisher=[[World Curling Tour]]|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Skip !! Third !! Second !! Lead !! Locale\n|-\n| [[Mike Anderson (curler)|Mike Anderson]] || [[Mike McLean (curler)|Mike McLean]] || [[Chris Van Huyse]] || [[Sean Harrison]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Evgeniy Arkhipov]] || [[Sergei Glukhov]] || [[Dmitry Mironov]] || [[Artur Razhabov]] || {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n|-\n| [[Roy Arndt]] || [[Kyle Duck]] || [[Jeff MacDonald (curler)|Jeff MacDonald]] || [[Stuart Sankey]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Mathew Camm]] (fourth) || [[Chris Gardner (curler)|Chris Gardner]] || [[Brad Kidd]] || [[Bryan Cochrane]] (skip) || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Nepean, Ontario|Nepean]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Robert Desjardins (curler)|Robert Desjardins]] || [[Frederic Lawton]] || [[Miguel Bernard]] || [[Martin Lavoie]] || {{flagicon|QC}} [[Saguenay, Quebec|Saguenay]], [[Quebec]]\n|-\n| [[Andrey Drozdov]] || [[Alexey Stukalskiy]] || [[Alexey Tselousov]] || [[Petr Dron]] || {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n|-\n| [[John Epping]] || [[Scott Bailey (curler)|Scott Bailey]] || [[Collin Mitchell]] || [[David Mathers (curler)|David Mathers]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Pete Fenson]] || [[Shawn Rojeski]] || [[Joe Polo]] || [[Ryan Brunt (curler)|Ryan Brunt]] || {{flagicon|MN}} [[Bemidji, Minnesota|Bemidji]], [[Minnesota]]\n|-\n| [[Pat Ferris]] || [[Andrew Fairfull]] || [[Craig Fairfull]] || [[Robert Larmer]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Grimsby]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Joe Frans]] || [[Ryan Werenich]] || [[Jeff Gorda]] || [[Shawn Kaufman]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Christopher Plys]] (fourth) || [[Tyler George]] (skip) || [[Rich Ruohonen]] || [[Colin Hufman]] || {{flagicon|MN}} [[Duluth, Minnesota|Duluth]], [[Minnesota]]\n|-\n| [[Brad Gushue]] || [[Brett Gallant]] || [[Adam Casey (curler)|Adam Casey]] || [[Geoff Walker (curler)|Geoff Walker]] || {{flagicon|NL}} [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]], [[Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n|-\n| [[Brent Ross]] (fourth) || [[Jake Higgs]] (skip) || [[Codey Maus]] || [[Bill Buchanan (curler)|Bill Buchanan]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Harriston, Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Steffen Mellemsetter]] || [[Markus H\u00f8iberg]] || [[Steffen Walstad]] || [[Magnus Nedregotten]] || {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Oppdal]], [[Norway]]\n|-\n| [[Glenn Howard]] || [[Wayne Middaugh]] || [[Brent Laing]] || [[Craig Savill]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Penetanguishene]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Mark Kean]] || [[Travis Fanset]] || [[Patrick Janssen]] || [[Tim March]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Craig Kochan]] || [[Phil Loevenmark]] || [[Andrew Clayton (curler)|Andrew Clayton]] || [[Geoff Chambers]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Alex Leichter]] || [[Brandon Corbett]] || [[Derek Corbett]] || [[Jeff Pulli]] || {{flagicon|NY}} [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|-\n| [[Mike McEwen (curler)|Mike McEwen]] || [[B. J. Neufeld]] || [[Matt Wozniak]] || [[Denni Neufeld]] || {{flagicon|MB}} [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]\n|-\n| [[Jean-Michel M\u00e9nard]] || [[Martin Cr\u00eate]] || [[\u00c9ric Sylvain]] || [[Philippe M\u00e9nard]] || {{flagicon|QC}} [[Gatineau]], [[Quebec]]\n|-\n| [[Robert Rumfeldt|Rob Rumfeldt]] || [[Adam Spencer (curler)|Adam Spencer]] || [[Scott Howard (curler)|Scott Howard]] || [[Scott Hodgson]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Jeff Stoughton]] || [[Jon Mead]] || [[Reid Carruthers]] || [[Mark Nichols (curler)|Mark Nichols]] || {{flagicon|MB}} [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]\n|-\n| [[Wayne Tuck, Jr.]] || [[Chad Allen (curler)|Chad Allen]] || [[Jay Allen (curler)|Jay Allen]] || [[Caleb Flaxey]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Brantford]], [[Ontario]]\n|-\n| [[Jake Walker (curler)|Jake Walker]] || [[Dayna Deruelle]] || [[Andrew McGaugh]] || [[Michael McGaugh]] || {{flagicon|ON}} [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]]\n|}\n\n===Knockout results===\n\n====A event====\n{{16TeamBracket-Compact-NoSeeds-Byes\n| RD1= First knockout\n| RD2= \n| RD3= \n| RD4= Qualifier 1\n| team-width= 150px\n\n| RD1-team03= {{flagicon|ON}} [[Mike Anderson (curler)|Mike Anderson]]\n| RD1-score03= 5\n| RD1-team04= {{flagicon|ON}} '''[[Wayne Tuck, Jr.]]'''\n| RD1-score04= '''8'''\n| RD1-team07= {{flagicon|ON}} '''[[Bryan Cochrane]]'''\n| RD1-score07= '''5'''\n| RD1-team08= {{flagicon|ON}} [[Roy Arndt]]\n| RD1-score08= 2\n| RD1-team11= {{flagicon|MN}} '''[[Tyler George]]'''\n| RD1-score11= '''5'''\n| RD1-team12= {{flagicon|ON}} [[Craig Kochan]]\n| RD1-score12= 3\n| RD1-team15= {{flagicon|MN}} [[Pete Fenson]]\n| RD1-score15= 5\n| RD1-team16= {{flagicon|QC}} '''[[Robert Desjardins (curler)|Robert Desjardins]]'''\n| RD1-score16= '''7'''\n\n| RD2-team01= {{flagicon|MB}} '''[[Jeff Stoughton]]'''\n| RD2-score01= '''5'''\n| RD2-team02= {{flagicon|ON}} [[Wayne Tuck, Jr.]]\n| RD2-score02= 3\n| RD2-team03= {{flagicon|ON}} '''[[Joe Frans]]'''\n| RD2-score03= '''6'''\n| RD2-team04= {{flagicon|ON}} [[Bryan Cochrane]]\n| RD2-score04= 2\n| RD2-team05= {{flagicon|NL}} '''[[Brad Gushue]]'''\n| RD2-score05= '''7'''\n| RD2-team06= {{flagicon|MN}} [[Tyler George]]\n| RD2-score06= 3\n| RD2-team07= {{flagicon|ON}} '''[[John Epping]]'''\n| RD2-score07= '''8'''\n| RD2-team08= {{flagicon|QC}} [[Robert Desjardins (curler)|Robert Desjardins]]\n| RD2-score08= 6\n\n| RD3-team01= {{flagicon|MB}} '''[[Jeff Stoughton]]'''\n| RD3-score01= '''6'''\n| RD3-team02= {{flagicon|ON}} [[Joe Frans]]\n| RD3-score02= 2\n| RD3-team03= {{flagicon|NL}} [[Brad Gushue]]\n| RD3-score03= 3\n| RD3-team04= {{flagicon|ON}} '''[[John Epping]]'''\n| RD3-score04=